  (
    'snapshot-company-fruitvaccine-1d68aa569e',
    'FruitVaccine',
    array['FruitVaccine']::text[],
    'Life Sciences',
    null,
    'Tracking',
    'Fruit Vaccine, Inc., an early-stage company based in Urbana, IL that was a spinoff of the University of Illinois.  The option agreement includes the ASU technology and Ip under the M21-011L “Chimeric virus-like particles based on fusion proteins with HIV gp41 co-expressed with Gag protein” invention developed by ASU inventors Hugh Mason and Tsafrir Mor, both Associate Professors, SOLS and Biodesign Center for Immunotherapy, Vaccines and Virotherapy, and Aigerim Kamzina Graduate Teaching Assistant, Biodesign Center for Immunotherapy, Vaccines and Virotherapy.  The CEO of the company, S. Indu Rupassara is also an inventor of the IP.  FruitVaccine is developing an edible vaccine administered via fruit (e.g., cherry tomatoes), which will immunize against the human respiratory syncytial virus (hRSV). All humans, especially infants and the elderly, are susceptible to hRSV Which mainly affects the lower respiratory system. Currently, the market doesn’t an hRSV vaccine or a fruit-based vaccine. An edible vaccine will be safer and more cost-effective than other vaccine forms and the FruitVaccine technology will be applicable to additional infectious diseases.',
    'FY24',
    'www.fruitvaccine.org',
    'hugh.mason@asu.edu',
